[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions can help a programmer read the code, help a compiler compile it, or help the program detect its own defects.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] For the latter, some programs check assertions by actually evaluating the predicate as they run.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Then, if it is not in fact true – an assertion failure – the program considers itself to be broken and typically deliberately crashes or throws an assertion failure exception.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Programmers can use assertions to help specify programs and to reason about program correctness.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, a precondition—an assertion placed at the beginning of a section of code—determines the set of states under which the programmer expects the code to execute.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] A postcondition—placed at the end—describes the expected state at the end of execution.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The example above uses the notation for including assertions used by C.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] That notation cannot be used in existing mainstream programming languages.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] However, programmers can include unchecked assertions using the comment feature of their programming language.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The braces included in the comment help distinguish this use of a comment from other uses.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Libraries may provide assertion features as well.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Several modern programming languages include checked assertions – statements that are checked at runtime or sometimes statically.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] If an assertion evaluates to false at runtime, an assertion failure results, which typically causes execution to abort.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This draws attention to the location at which the logical inconsistency is detected and can be preferable to the behaviour that would otherwise result.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The use of assertions helps the programmer design, develop, and reason about a program.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In languages such as Eiffel, assertions form part of the design process; other languages, such as C and Java, use them only to check assumptions at runtime.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In both cases, they can be checked for validity at runtime, but can usually also be suppressed.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions can function as a form of documentation: they can describe the state the code expects to find before it runs (its preconditions), and the state the code expects to result in when it is finished running (postconditions); they can also specify invariants of a class.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Eiffel integrates such assertions into the language and automatically extracts them to document the class.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This forms an important part of the method of design by contract.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This approach is also useful in languages that do not explicitly support it: the advantage of using assertion statements rather than assertions in comments is that the program can check the assertions every time it runs; if the assertion no longer holds, an error can be reported.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This prevents the code from getting out of sync with the assertions.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, the following demonstrates design by contract in C++ (using C++26 contracts).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] An assertion may be used to verify that an assumption made by the programmer during the implementation of the program remains valid when the program is executed.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In Java, `%` is the *remainder* operator (*modulo*), and in Java, if its first operand is negative, the result can also be negative (unlike the modulo used in mathematics).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer has assumed that `total` is non-negative, so that the remainder of a division by 2 will always be 0 or 1.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The assertion makes this assumption explicit: if `countNumberOfUsers` does return a negative value, the program may have a bug.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] A major advantage of this technique is that when an error does occur, it is detected immediately and directly, rather than later through often obscure effects.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Since an assertion failure usually reports the code location, one can often pinpoint the error without further debugging.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions are also sometimes placed at points where the execution is not supposed to reach.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, assertions could be placed at the `default` clause of the `switch` statement in languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Any case that the programmer does not handle intentionally will raise an error, and the program will abort rather than silently continuing in an erroneous state.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In D such an assertion is added automatically when a `switch` statement doesn't contain a `default` clause.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In Java, assertions have been a part of the language since version 1.4.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertion failures result in raising an `AssertionError` when the program is run with the appropriate flags, without which the assert statements are ignored.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In C, they are added on by the standard header `<assert.h>` defining `assert(*assertion*)` as a macro that signals an error in the case of failure, usually terminating the program.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In C++, both `<assert.h>` and `<cassert>` headers provide the `assert` macro.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The danger of assertions is that they may cause side effects either by changing memory data or by changing thread timing.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions should be implemented carefully, so they cause no side effects on program code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertion constructs in a language allow for easy test-driven development (TDD) without the use of a third-party library.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In C#, there is no assertion macro or keyword, but instead classes `System.Diagnostics.Debug` and `System.Diagnostics.Trace` which provide `Assert()` methods.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] During the development cycle, the programmer will typically run the program with assertions enabled.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] When an assertion failure occurs, the programmer is immediately notified of the problem.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Many assertion implementations will also halt the program's execution: this is useful, since if the program continued to run after an assertion violation occurred, it might corrupt its state and make the cause of the problem more difficult to locate.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Using the information provided by the assertion failure (such as the location of the failure and perhaps a stack trace, or even the full program state if the environment supports core dumps or if the program is running in a debugger), the programmer can usually fix the problem.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Thus, assertions provide a very powerful tool in debugging.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] When a program is deployed to production, assertions are typically turned off to avoid any overhead or side effects they may have.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In some cases, assertions are completely absent from deployed code, such as in C/C++ assertions via macros.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In other cases, such as Java, assertions are present in the deployed code and can be turned on in the field for debugging.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions may also be used to promise the compiler that a given edge condition is not actually reachable, thereby permitting certain optimizations that would not otherwise be possible.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In this case, disabling the assertions could actually reduce performance.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions that are checked at compile time are called static assertions.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Static assertions are particularly useful in compile-time template metaprogramming, but can also be used in low-level languages like C by introducing illegal code if (and only if) the assertion fails.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] C11 and C++11 support static assertions directly through `static_assert`.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because the compiler will not allow two case labels with the same constant.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
