[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Using unit-tests as a design specification has one significant advantage over other design methods: The design document (the unit-tests themselves) can itself be used to verify the implementation.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] The tests will never pass unless the developer implements a solution according to the design.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing lacks some of the accessibility of a diagrammatic specification such as a UML diagram, but they may be generated from the unit test using automated tools.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Most modern languages have free tools (usually available as extensions to IDEs).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Free tools, like those based on the xUnit framework, outsource to another system the graphical rendering of a view for human consumption.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing is the cornerstone of extreme programming, which relies on an automated unit testing framework.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] This automated unit testing framework can be either third party, e.g., xUnit, or created within the development group.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming uses the creation of unit tests for test-driven development.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] The developer writes a unit test that exposes either a software requirement or a defect.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] This test will fail because either the requirement isn't implemented yet, or because it intentionally exposes a defect in the existing code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Then, the developer writes the simplest code to make the test, along with other tests, pass.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Most code in a system is unit tested, but not necessarily all paths through the code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming mandates a "test everything that can possibly break" strategy, over the traditional "test every execution path" method.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] This leads developers to develop fewer tests than classical methods, but this isn't really a problem, more a restatement of fact, as classical methods have rarely ever been followed methodically enough for all execution paths to have been thoroughly tested.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming simply recognizes that testing is rarely exhaustive (because it is often too expensive and time-consuming to be economically viable) and provides guidance on how to effectively focus limited resources.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Crucially, the test code is considered a first class project artifact in that it is maintained at the same quality as the implementation code, with all duplication removed.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Developers release unit testing code to the code repository in conjunction with the code it tests.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Extreme programming's thorough unit testing allows the benefits mentioned above, such as simpler and more confident code development and refactoring, simplified code integration, accurate documentation, and more modular designs.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] These unit tests are also constantly run as a form of regression test.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing is also critical to the concept of Emergent Design, which develops software design iteratively through short test-driven development cycles of writing a unit test, making it pass, and refactoring; unit tests provide the regression safety net that makes continuous refactoring safe.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] An automated testing framework provides features for automating test execution and can accelerate writing and running tests.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Frameworks have been developed for a wide variety of programming languages.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Generally, frameworks are third-party, not distributed with a compiler or integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Tests can be written without using a framework to exercise the code under test using assertions, exception handling, and other control flow mechanisms to verify behavior and report failure.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Some note that testing without a framework is valuable since there is a barrier to entry for the adoption of a framework, and that having some tests is better than none – but once a framework is in place, adding tests can be easier.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] In some frameworks advanced test features are missing and must be hand-coded.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Some programming languages directly support unit testing.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Their grammar allows the direct declaration of unit tests without importing a library (whether third party or standard).
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Additionally, the Boolean conditions of the unit tests can be expressed in the same syntax as Boolean expressions used in non-unit test code, such as what is used for `if` and `while` statements.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/unit-testing] Some languages do not have built-in unit-testing support but have established unit testing libraries or frameworks.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The SUnit framework was ported to Java by Kent Beck and Erich Gamma as JUnit which gained wide popularity.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] Adaptations to other languages were also popular which led some to claim that the structured, object-oriented style works well with popular languages including Java and C#.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The name of an adaptation is often a variation of "SUnit" with the "S" replaced with an abbreviation of the target language name.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] For example, JUnit for Java and RUnit for R.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The term "xUnit" refers to any such adaptation where "x" is a placeholder for the language-specific prefix.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The xUnit frameworks are often used for unit testing – testing an isolated unit of code – but can be used for any level of software testing including integration and system.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] An xUnit framework has the following general architecture.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A test case is the smallest part of a test that generally encodes a simple path through the software under test.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The test case code prepares input data and environmental state, invokes the software under test and verifies expected results.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A programmer writes the code for each test case.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A test case is implemented with one or more assertions that validate expected results.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] Generally, the framework provides assertion functionality.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A framework may provide a way to use custom assertions.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A test suite is a collection of related test cases.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] They share a framework which allows for reuse of environment setup and cleanup code.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] Generally, a test runner may run the cases of a suite in any order so the programmer should not depend on top-to-bottom execution order.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A test fixture (also known as a test context) provides the environment for each test case of a suite.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] Generally, a fixture is configured to setup a known, good, runtime environment before tests run, and to cleanup the environment after.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The fixture is configured with one or more functions that setup and cleanup state.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The test runner runs each setup function before each case and runs each cleanup function after.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A test runner is a program that runs tests and reports results.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] The program is often part of a framework.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] A test runner may produce results in various formats.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] Often, a common and default format is human-readable, plain-text.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] Additionally, the runner may produce structured output.
[src:xunit-dotnet-lib/xunit] JUnit) can output XML that can be used by a continuous integration system such as Jenkins and Atlassian Bamboo.
